# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dodge-mirada
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The **1955 Dodge** car lineup, consisting of the entry-level Coronet, Royal, and ornate Custom Royal, was a major departure for the company.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Driven almost out of business in 1953 and 1954, the Chrysler Corporation was revived with a $250 million loan from Prudential and new models designed by Virgil Exner.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The Dodge lineup was positioned as the mainstream line in Chrysler's hierarchy, between DeSoto and Plymouth.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The 1955 Dodge was all-new with a 120 in (3048 mm) wheelbase and 212.1 in (5387 mm) overall length, longer than the 1954 cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] They shared their basic mechanicals with the DeSoto Custom, but had distinct styling.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] These cars lasted through the 1956 model year before being replaced by an all-new 1957.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The **Coronet** (and **Suburban** station wagon) was the base model.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] This was the only line to feature the 230 in3 (3.8 L) *Getaway* I6 as well as the 270 in3 (4.4 L) *Red Ram* V8.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Coronets were available in all body styles except the convertible.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Sedans feature "Coronet" badges on the fenders, while the station wagons are called "Suburban".
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Although the hardtop coupe was officially named "Lancer", it wore only "Coronet" badges.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Turn signals were standard on the Royal and Custom Royal models but optional on the base Coronet.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The **Royal** (and **Sierra** wagon) were the next step up.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Featuring only the V8 engine, the Royal also lacked the 2-door sedan and wagon models available in the Coronet line.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Early hardtop coupes lack the "Lancer" script, although they were officially Lancers, but later models wore "Royal Lancer" badges.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The flagship model was the **Custom Royal**.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] All hardtop coupe and Custom Royal-only convertible models were called "Custom Royal Lancer".
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The Custom line featured unique chrome tailfins (although early model year cars went without this trim), special tail light surrounds, and an upscale interior.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Backup lights were standard on the Custom line but optional on all others.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The Custom Royal also featured the hemi 270 CID Super Red Ram engine.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The **La Femme** was a special package oriented towards women, who made up an increasing share of Dodge buyers.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] It came in Heather Rose and Sapphire White colors and included a cape, boots, umbrella, and shoulder bag that matched the floral tapestry-like fabrics.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Changes to the car include built-in compartments in the seatbacks to hold these accessories.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The 1956 **D-500** was a high-performance model derived from the standard 1956 Dodge but differing in many ways.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] It included a heavy duty suspension and other chassis upgrades from the New Yorker and Imperial lines, upgraded brakes, and a high-performance 315 in3 (5.2 L) Hemi-head V8.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] A four-barrel Carter carburetor pushed output to 260 hp (194 kW) and 330 lb·ft (447 N·m).
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The 3-speed manual transmission was standard, with the PowerFlite 2-speed automatic as an option.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] A rare NASCAR-specific option was the D-500-1(Dash-1), which upped power to 285 hp (213 kW).
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The D-500 originally used only the Coronet 2-door sedan and Royal Lancer hardtop and convertible bodies.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] For the 1957 model year, Chrysler embarked on a second total linewide redesign.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Virgil Exner's "Forward Design" brought about cars that were bigger and more sleek than anything before, and instantly put a company that had traditionally regarded styling as unimportant on the forefront of automotive design.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Unfortunately, two total redesigns in as many years resulted in severe build quality and rust problems, so that many 1957 Chryslers, Dodges, and Plymouths were off the road within three years of their purchase.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] While many of the quality issues were resolved for the 1958 model year, which brought about some minor styling tweaks, a recession struck that was particularly damaging to sales of mid-range cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Dodge production had exceeded 337,000 cars for 1957 but the 1958 total fell by over half to less than 140,000, although some of this loss was due to negative publicity from the cars' poor quality control.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] 1959 Dodges were facelifted to gain a heavy, drooping look with hooded headlamps.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Production for the model year totaled 156,395 cars, a modest increase over 1958.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The highlight of the lineup was the performance-oriented D-500 package.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Power came from either a 230 cu in (4 L) flathead straight six or one of two 270 cu in (4 L) V8s.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The regular Red Ram V8 was standard on the Royal and optional on the Coronet.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] A hemi V8 (the Super Red Ram) was standard on the Custom Royal.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] A rare Power Pack was optional, consisting of a four-barrel Carter carburetor and dual exhausts good for 193 hp (144 kW; 196 PS) with the Hemi engine.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] Two transmissions were offered: a three-speed manual with optional overdrive and Chrysler's two-speed PowerFlite automatic.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The PowerFlite was controlled by a dash-mounted lever, though this was changed to a push-button setup for 1956.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] The cars used a special coil spring/kingpin suspension in front and regular leaf springs and a live axle at the rear.
[src:dodge-mirada/1955-dodge] A six-volt electrical system was updated to 12 volts in 1956.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:dodge-mirada/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The functional design and development of a modern motor vehicle is typically done by a large team from many different disciplines also included within automotive engineering, however, design roles are not associated with requirements for professional- or chartered-engineer qualifications.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Automotive design in this context focuses primarily on developing the visual appearance or aesthetics of vehicles, while also becoming involved in the creation of product concepts.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Automotive design as a professional vocation is practiced by designers who may have an art background and a degree in industrial design or in transportation design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] For the terminology used in the field, see the glossary of automotive design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The task of the design team is usually split into three main aspects: exterior design, interior design, and color and trim design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Graphic design is also an aspect of automotive design; this is generally shared amongst the design team as the lead designer sees fit.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The design focuses not only on the isolated outer shape of automobile parts, but concentrates on the combination of form and function, starting from the vehicle package.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The aesthetic value will need to correspond to ergonomic functionality and utility features as well.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Though not all the new vehicular gadgets are to be designated as factory standard items, some of them may be integral to determining the future course of any specific vehicular models.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The design team(s) responsible for the exterior of the vehicle develops the proportions, shape, and surface details of the vehicle.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Exterior design is first done by a series of manual sketches and digital drawings.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Progressively, more detailed drawings are executed and approved by appropriate layers of management, followed by digital rendering to images.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Consumer feedback is generally sought at this point to help iteratively refine vehicle concepts according to the targeted market and will continue throughout the rest of the design refinement process.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] After more progressive refinement, industrial plasticine and or digital models are developed from and along with the drawings and images.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The data from these models are then used to create quarter-scale and finally full-sized mock-ups of the final design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] With three- and five-axis CNC milling machines, the clay model is first designed in a computer program and then "carved" using the machine and large amounts of clay.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Even in times of photorealistic (three-dimensional) software and virtual models on power walls, the clay model is still the most important tool for a final evaluation of the exterior design of a vehicle and, therefore, is used throughout the industry.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The designer responsible for the vehicles' interior develops the proportions, shape, placement, and surfaces for the instrument panel, seats, door trim panels, headliner, pillar trims, etc.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Here the emphasis is on ergonomics and the comfort of the passengers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The procedure here is the same as with exterior design (sketch, digital model, and clay model).
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The color and trim (or color and materials) designer is responsible for the research, design, and development of all interior and exterior colors and materials used on a vehicle.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] These include paints, plastics, fabric designs, leather, grains, carpet, headliner, wood trim, and so on.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Color, contrast, texture, and pattern must be carefully combined to give the vehicle a unique interior environment experience.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Designers work closely with exterior and interior designers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Designers draw inspiration from other design disciplines such as industrial design, fashion, home furnishing, architecture, and sometimes product design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Specific research is done into global trends to design for projects two to three model years in the future.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Trend boards are created from this research to keep track of design influences as they relate to the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The designer then uses this information to develop themes and concepts that are then further refined and tested on the vehicle models.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The design team also develops graphics for items, such as badges, decals, dials, switches, kick or tread strips, or liveries.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The sketches and rendering are transformed into 3D digital surface modeling and rendering for real-time evaluation with Math data in the initial stages.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] During the development process succeeding phases will require the 3D model fully developed to meet the aesthetic requirements of a designer as well as all engineering and manufacturing requirements.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The fully developed CAS digital model will be re-developed for manufacturing meeting the Class-A surface standards that involve both technical as well as aesthetics.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] A Product Engineering team will further develop this data.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] These modelers usually have a background in industrial design or sometimes tooling engineering in the case of some Class-A modelers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Autodesk Alias and ICEM Surf are the two most widely used software tools for Class-A development.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Uniform surface continuity is critical to ensure Class-A surface standards.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The continuity of the areas is between the quality grades G0 through G3, with G3 guaranteeing the cleanest patch-to-patch transitions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The design process occurs concurrently with other product engineers who will be engineering the styling data for meeting performance, manufacturing, and safety regulations.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] From mid-phase, back-and-forth interactions between the designers and product engineers culminate into a finished product being manufacturing-ready.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Apart from this the engineering team parallelly works in the following areas.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Product Engineering (Body In White Sheetmetal Design and Plastic engineering), NVH Development team, Prototype development, Powertrain engineering, Physical Vehicle validation, Tool and Die development, and Manufacturing process design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The design team for a specific model consists of a chief designer and an exterior as well as an interior designer.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] In some cases, all three roles are done by one designer.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Several junior designers are involved in the development process as well and make specific contributions all overseen by the chief designer.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Apart from this, the color and trim designer works closely with other designers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The clay model team and digital model team work closely with the styling team all located within the studio.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Apart from this, there would be studio heads, studio managers, and prototype engineers who would work across all teams in the studio.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The total team size for developing a full car usually ranges from 25 to 40 members and the development time lasts for more than 24 months until signed-off for tooling and production.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] After that, a smaller team would be working until the vehicle launch.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] In the early days of the automobile, manufacturers prioritized function over form, focusing on building simple, reliable, and affordable vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Some automakers began incorporating artists to combine styling with engineering.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Visual appeal remained secondary to technical and safety advancements until the 1930s, an era that, despite its financial challenges, became a high point of creative coachbuilding.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] World War II halted the momentum, but it evolved when the industry restarted in the late 1940s, heavily influenced by the Jet Age.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] However, the artwork and models created by designers are routinely destroyed so as not to be seen by competing automakers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Great car designers are visionary artists who can translate their ideas from sketches and models into tangible vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Their work is a blend of artistry and engineering, shaped by collaborations with engineers who help bring their creative concepts to life.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Some automobile forms have served to influence the success and careers of successive designers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] In the United States, automotive design reached a turning point in the 1920s when the American national automobile market began reaching saturation.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] To maintain unit sales, General Motors head Alfred P.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Sloan Jr. suggested annual model-year design changes to convince car owners that they needed to buy a new replacement each year, an idea borrowed from the bicycle industry (though Sloan usually gets the credit or blame).
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Critics called his strategy planned obsolescence.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Sloan preferred the term "dynamic obsolescence".
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] This strategy had far-reaching effects on the auto business, the field of product design, and eventually the American economy.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The smaller automakers could not maintain the pace and expense of yearly re-styling.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Henry Ford did not like the model-year change because he clung to an engineer's notions of simplicity, the economics of scale, and design integrity.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] GM surpassed Ford's sales in 1931 and became the dominant company in the industry thereafter.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The frequent design changes also made it necessary to use a body-on-frame rather than the lighter but less adaptable monocoque design used by most European automakers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] In the 1930s, Chrysler's innovations with aerodynamics helped launch the Chrysler Airflow in 1934, which was revolutionary and radical compared to contemporary vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] However, inadequate consumer acceptance of the advanced appearance of the cars forced a re-design of succeeding models of the Airflow.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] This marketing experience made the entire industry take note of the high risks involved in incorporating major design advancements into their production cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] A major influence on American auto styling and marketing was Harley Earl, who is credited with inventing the idea of a concept car, and who brought the tailfin and other aeronautical design references to auto design starting with the rear fenders of the 1948 Cadillac.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Another notable designer was Chrysler group's designer Virgil Exner, who developed the Forward look design in the mid-1950s.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Exner is also credited with using wind tunnel testing to justify incorporating tailfins, thus moving the company away from boxy-looking cars into more aerodynamic and futuristic designs that were influenced by rockets after WWII.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Other influential automotive designers include Raymond Loewy, who was responsible for a number of Studebaker vehicles such as the Avanti, and Gordon Buehrig, who was responsible for the Auburn 851, as well as the Cord 810 and 812.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Starting in the 1960s, Dick Teague, who spent most of his career with American Motors Corporation (AMC), originated the concept of using interchangeable body panels so as to create a wide array of different vehicles using the same stampings, starting with the AMC Cavalier.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Teague was responsible for automotive designs such as the two-seat AMC AMX muscle car, the subcompact Gremlin, the Pacer, and Matador coupe, as well as the original and market segment-creating, Jeep Cherokee.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Additionally during the 1960s, Ford's first-generation Ford Mustang and Thunderbird marked another era leading into new market segments from Detroit.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The Ford Mustang achieved record sales in its first year of production and established the pony car segment.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Personal injury litigation has affected the design and appearance of the car in the 20th century.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Until World War I, most automakers were concerned with mechanical reliability rather than the external appearance of their cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Later, luxury and aesthetics became a demand, and also an effective marketing tool.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Designs from each nation with their own strong cultural identity are reflected in their exterior and interior designs.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] World War II slowed the progress, but after the early 1950s, Italian designers set the trend and remained the driving force until the early part of the 1980s.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] In France notable designs came from Bugatti and Avions Voisin.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Of the mass-selling cars, Citroën launched their vehicles with innovative designs and engineering, aided by the styling of Flaminio Bertoni as evident from the Citroën DS.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] After World War II, with the decline of the coachbuilding industry, French automakers (except Citroën) followed British and other popular trends until they gained financial stability.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] During the 1980s, manufacturers like Renault cultivated their own strong design identities with designers like Patrick Le Quément.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Peugeot, which was dependent on Pininfarina since the early post-war period, later established its own brand identity from the 1980s onwards.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Its other company, Citroën, still retains its distinctive French innovations for its designs.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Great Britain was Europe's leading manufacturer of automobiles until the late-1960s.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] During that era, there were more British-based automakers than in the rest of Europe combined.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The British automobile industry catered to all segments ranging from compact, budget, sports, utility, and luxury-type cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Car design in Britain was markedly different from other European designs largely because British designers were not influenced by other European art or design movements, as well as the British clay modelers, used a different sweep set.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] British cars until World War II were sold in most of the British colonies.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Innovations in vehicle packaging and chassis engineering combined with global familiarity with British designs meant vehicles were acceptable to public tastes at that time.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] British skilled resources such as panel beaters, die machinists, and clay modelers were also available partly due to their involvement with the motorsport industry.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Still, during the 1960s, British manufacturers sought professional help from Italian designers and studios such as Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, and Pininfarina.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Notable British contributions to automobile designs were the Morris Mini by Alec Issigonis, several Jaguar Cars by Sir William Lyons and Malcolm Sayer, Aston Martin DB Series, and several cars from Triumph and MG.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Ford Europe, based in Great Britain, is notable for the Ford Sierra line, a work of Uwe Bahnsen, Robert Lutz, and Patrick le Quément.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Other notable British designers include William Towns for Aston Martin, and David Bache for Land Rover and Range Rover, and Ian Callum for Jaguar.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] During the complex changes in the British car industry in the 1990s and beyond, a mix of designers worked on all of the remaining mainstream brands under one design director and in one studio.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The director most involved was Geoff Upex, with his team of Richard Woolley, Dave Saddington, George Thomson, Alan Mobberley, and Martin Peach (colour and trim).
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Germany is often considered the birthplace of industrial design with the Bauhaus School of Design, before it was closed down by the Nazi regime.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Ferdinand Porsche and his family played a significant role in German design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Mercedes-Benz passenger cars were also in the luxury segment and played an important role in German car design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] After the 1980s, German design evolved into a distinctive Teutonic style often to complement their highly engineered cars suited to Autobahns.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The early German design clues of the present-day owe some part to Italian designers like Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, and Giorgetto Giugiaro.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] During the mid- and late-20th century one of the most influential coach builders/designers in Germany was Karmann.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] German designs started gaining popularity after the 1980s, notable after the formation of Audi.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Volkswagen, which was dependent on Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Karmann, later formed the contemporary design language along with Audi.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] BMW entered the automobile design with sporty-looking everyday sedans using Giovanni Michelotti.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] These models were later enhanced by Ercole Spada into the 1980s, and Klaus Luthe until the mid-1990s.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The American-born designer Chris Bangle was hired by BMW in the late-1990s to redefine the brand.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Bangle incorporated new single-press technology for compound curves to add controversial styling elements to his designs.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The Porsche family contribution was instrumental in the evolution of Porsche cars, while the Italian designer Bruno Sacco helped create various Mercedes Models from the 1960s to the 1990s.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] In Italy, Fiat and Alfa Romeo played a major role in car design.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Many coachbuilders were dependent on these two major manufacturers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Italian manufacturers had a large presence in motorsports leading to several sport car manufacturers like Ferrari, Lancia, Lamborghini, Maserati, etc.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] During the late-1950s, Italian automobile designs gained global popularity coinciding with the modern fashion and architecture at that time around the world.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Various design and technical schools in Turin turned out designers on a large scale.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] By the late-1960s, almost all Italian coachbuilders transformed into design studios catering to automakers around the world.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The trend continued in the 1990s when the Japanese and Korean manufacturers sourced designs from these styling studios.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Some Italian designers whose design services were sought globally include Aldo Brovarone, Giovanni Michelotti, Ercole Spada, Bruno Sacco, Marcello Gandini, Giorgetto Giugiaro, and Walter de Silva.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Sweden had Volvo and Saab as domestic automakers, and the nation's northern location required that cars needed to withstand Nordic climate conditions.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] The Scandinavian design elements are known for their minimalism and simplicity.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] One of the early original Scandinavian designs was the Saab 92001 by Sixten Sason and Gunnar Ljungström.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Koenigsegg, founded in the 1990s, became Sweden's first domestic producer of high end sports cars, with many of their models featuring in house designs by Swedish designers.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Before World War II and until the early-1990s, Czechoslovakia had a strong presence in the automotive industry with manufacturers like Škoda, Jawa, Tatra, CZ, Praga, and Zetor.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] Czech automobiles were generally known for their originality in mechanical simplicity and designs were remarkably Bohemian as evident from Tatra cars and Jawa motorcycles.
[src:dodge-mirada/automotive-design] During the Communist regime, the design started falling back and ultimately the domestic automakers ended up as subsidiaries of EU-based companies.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In the automotive industry, **rebadging** (also known as **badge engineering**, an intentionally ironic misnomer in that little or no actual engineering takes place) is a form of market segmentation used by automobile manufacturers around the world.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] To allow for product differentiation without designing or engineering a new model or brand (at high cost or risk), a manufacturer creates a distinct automobile by applying a new "badge" or trademark (brand, logo, or manufacturer's name/make/marque) to an existing product line.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The term originated with the practice of replacing an automobile's emblems to create an ostensibly new model sold by a different maker.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Changes may be confined to swapping badges and emblems, or may encompass minor styling differences, as with cosmetic changes to headlights, taillights, front and rear fascias, and even outer body skins.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] More extreme examples involve differing engines and drivetrains.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The objective is "to spread the huge development costs of a new vehicle over as many cars as possible".
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] An example is General Motors' rebadging of the Camaro as the Firebird, a successful model from the 1960s through to the 2000s.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In most cases, consumers are interested in each brand's focus "on the unique elements of styling and driving characteristics".
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Some cars would not be marketed without the cost savings that are obtained from this practice, and carmakers can develop many "different models – all wearing different badges – off the one platform".
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In several countries including Japan, manufacturers often use the phrase "OEM supply" or "OEM-supplied" to denote vehicles that are a rebadged model from or for other manufacturers.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Although platform sharing can often involve rebadging and rebranding, it can extend further, as the design may be used across multiple configurations.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For example, a single platform may underpin a sedan, hatchback, or SUV/CUV body designs.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Automotive industry rebadging can be compared with white-label products in other consumer goods industries, such as consumer electronics and power tools.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The first known case of badge engineering appeared in 1917 with the Texan automobile assembled in Fort Worth, Texas, that made use of Elcar bodies made in Elkhart, Indiana.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] "Probably the industry's first example of one car becoming another" occurred in 1926 when Nash Motors' newly introduced smaller-sized Ajax models were discontinued in 1926 after over 22,000 Ajax cars were sold during the brand's inaugural year.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The chairman and CEO of the company, Charles W.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Nash, ordered that the Ajax models be marketed as the "Nash Light Six", Nash being a known and respected automobile brand.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Production was stopped for two days so Nash emblems, hubcaps, and radiator shells could be exchanged on all unshipped Ajax cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Conversion kits were also distributed at no charge to Ajax owners to transform their cars and protect the investment they had made in purchasing an automobile made by Nash.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Starting with the beginning of General Motors in 1909, chassis and platforms were shared with all brands.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] GMC, which historically was a truck builder, began to offer its products branded as Chevrolet, and vehicles produced by GM were built on common platforms shared with Chevrolet, Oakland, Oldsmobile, Buick, and Cadillac.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Exterior appearances were gradually upgraded between these vehicle brands.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] This was partly because all bodywork was provided by Fisher Body which was bought by GM in 1925, and the introduction of the Art and Color Section in 1928, directed by Harley Earl.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For the 1958 model year, GM was promoting its fiftieth year of production and introduced anniversary models for each brand; Cadillac, Buick, Oldsmobile, Pontiac, and Chevrolet.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The 1958 models shared an almost identical appearance on all models for each brand and made special luxury models with a shared appearance; Cadillac Eldorado Seville, Buick Limited Riviera, Oldsmobile Starfire 98, Pontiac Bonneville Catalina, and the Chevrolet Bel-Air Impala.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] A later example was Wolseley Motors after it was bought out by William Morris.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] After World War I, "Wolseley started to lose its identity and eventually succumbed to badge engineering." This was repeated with the consolidation of Austin Motor Company and the Nuffield Organization (parent company of Morris Motors) to form the British Motor Corporation (BMC).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The rationalization of production to gain efficiencies "did not extend to marketing", and each "model was adapted, by variation in trim and accessories, to appeal to customer loyalties for whom the badge denoting the company of origin was an important selling advantage ...
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] 'Badge Engineering', as it became known, was symptomatic of a policy of sales competition between the constituent organizations".
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The ultimate example of BMC badge engineering was the 1962 BMC ADO16 which was available badged as a Morris, MG, Austin, Wolseley, Riley and the upmarket Vanden Plas.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] A year earlier, the Mini was also available as Austin, Morris, Riley, and Wolseley – the latter two having slightly bigger boots.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Badge engineering often occurs when an individual manufacturer (such as the regional Big Threes of the United States, Europe, and Japan) owns a portfolio of different brands and markets the same car under different brands and nameplates.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The practice is used for multiple reasons.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In one example, a company may do so to expand its range of different brands in a market without the cost of developing completely new models.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In the United States, General Motors may sell a car through each brand; for example, the Chevrolet Tahoe, GMC Yukon, and Cadillac Escalade each share a common body.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In another example, the same model is rebadged when it is sold in different regions and markets.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In Australia, during the 1980s and 1990s, the Button car plan required imported Nissans and Toyotas to adopt Ford and Holden (GM) nameplates.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In the United Kingdom, Opel-produced vehicles are marketed under the Vauxhall brand; when sold in the United States, Opels were marketed as Saturns, Chevrolets, and Buicks.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Conversely, the Australian Holden brand was never sold in North America, but the Holden Monaro and Holden Commodore were sold under the Pontiac (Pontiac GTO, Pontiac G8), Chevrolet (Chevrolet SS), and Buick (Buick Regal Sportback/Buick Regal TourX) nameplates.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Another way badge engineering may occur is when two separate manufacturers trade products, filling gaps in their respective product lineups.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] During the 1990s, Honda and Isuzu entered into such an agreement, with Isuzu marketing the first-generation Honda Odyssey as the Isuzu Oasis as its first minivan.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] During the late 2000s and early 2010s, the Volkswagen Routan was a rebranded version of the Dodge Grand Caravan, supplied as Volkswagen sought to re-enter the North American minivan segment without the investment of federalizing its design.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Assembled by Chrysler with a Chrysler powertrain, the Routan received its own styling and content features as well as a standard "sportier suspension and steering".
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] (right) are two mechanically, internally, and near-externally identical cars that share the majority of their components, however feature various different stylistic elements to cater to the design language of each brand.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In Japan, automobile manufacturers differed in the marketing of their product ranges.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In contrast to marketing a single vehicle under multiple brand names (with minor changes to exterior bodywork), Japanese manufacturers marketed vehicles through multiple sales networks, with a distinct vehicle being sold under various model nameplates (from a single manufacturer).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Toyota marketed the Corolla in Japan exclusively at *Toyota Corolla Store* locations; at *Toyota Auto Store* locations, it was named the Toyota Sprinter.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Nissan sold the Nissan Cedric through its *Nissan Bluebird Store* network, with the identical Nissan Gloria through the *Nissan Prince Store* network.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Honda previously marketed the Honda Accord through multiple sales networks, marketing the Accord through the *Honda Clio* network and renaming it as the Honda Vigor for *Honda Verno* locations (conversely, the Vigor was renamed the Honda Inspire for the Clio network).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The practice of producing multiple versions of the same vehicle would eventually lead to distinct vehicles produced for export.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In North America, the Toyota Sprinter was marketed as the Chevrolet Nova (and the Geo Prizm that replaced it).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Honda Vigor and Inspire were marketed as the Acura Vigor and TL; Nissan sold the Gloria in the United States as the Infiniti M45.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Two automakers can also pool resources by operating a joint venture to create a product and then selling each as their own.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For example, General Motors and Toyota formed NUMMI.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The vehicles produced from this venture (though not necessarily at NUMMI itself) included the Toyota Sprinter/Chevrolet Prizm, and later the Toyota Matrix/Pontiac Vibe.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In another agreement, Ford and Nissan developed and produced the Mercury Villager and Nissan Quest minivans from 1993 through 2002.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Another example was the cooperative work between Volkswagen and Ford to develop the VW Sharan, Ford Galaxy, and SEAT Alhambra.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Another example was the joint venture of Mitsubishi and Chrysler that resulted in vehicles produced by Diamond-Star Motors that were marketed under various nameplates from 1985 until 1993.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In China, foreign manufacturers were required to form a joint venture with a local manufacturer to manufacture automobiles in the country.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Prior to 2022, the Chinese government dictates that no more than two joint ventures are allowed for each foreign investor.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Larger foreign manufacturers often set up two joint ventures to maximize the market reach, including Toyota (FAW Toyota and GAC Toyota), Ford (JMC-Ford and Changan Ford), Volkswagen (SAIC-VW and FAW-VW) and Honda (Dongfeng Honda and Guangqi Honda).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] To distribute the production and sales rights to each joint venture, manufacturers often resort to a similar strategy deployed in Japan: simply producing the exact model under two different names with minor changes to exterior bodywork.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] GAC Toyota has produced the Levin as a twin model to the FAW Toyota-built Corolla and the Wildlander as the alternative to the RAV4.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Honda awarded several models to two joint ventures, which spawned the Breeze from the original CR-V, the Elysion from the Odyssey, the XR-V from the HR-V, and others.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In other cases, foreign manufacturers may also rebadge a model developed by its partner, sometimes for exports to other markets.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Examples include the second generation Chevrolet Captiva which is an export version of the Baojun 530 made by SAIC-GM-Wuling, or the Ford Territory, a reworked version of the Yusheng S330 developed by Jiangling Motors (JMC).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Badge engineering could be used as a strategy to lengthen the life cycle of a vehicle.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] After a product has reached the end of its life cycle, it may be transferred to another brand, mostly from the same holding company or joint venture.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Examples include the SEAT Exeo, a rebadged Audi A4 B7 with reworked styling, which was built in Spain from used production tooling from the Audi plant in Ingolstadt after the A4 B7 production had ended.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The tooling was dismantled from Ingolstadt and was sent to the SEAT manufacturing plant in Martorell, Spain, to be reinstalled.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Another example is the Dongfeng Fengdu MX6, which was produced after the near-identical Nissan X-Trail (T31) production had ended, and the Maruti Suzuki Zen Estilo, which is based on the then-recently discontinued Suzuki MR Wagon.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The advantage of this strategy is amortized tooling costs, which means the vehicle can be produced at a higher margin of profit (or a lower price, or both).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Badge engineering occurs in the luxury-type market segments.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] An automobile manufacturer will use a model from its mainstream brand as a basis for a model under a premium marque by upgrading its features, technology, and/or styling.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Along with visible cosmetic differences, premium models may also receive upgraded drivetrains.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] An example of this is that Ford Motor Company marketed its mainstream Ford Fusion mid-size sedan as the Lincoln MKZ; the Ford Expedition SUV is sold as the Lincoln Navigator.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] A more controversial example was the Aston Martin Cygnet, a rebadged version of the Toyota iQ city car (intended to comply with EU emissions regulations).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] While fitted with model-specific trim and a luggage set, the Cygnet nearly tripled the price of the iQ.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Alternatively, VW Group under Ferdinand Piëch used the reverse of this in some circumstances, engineering the more luxurious model first and then removing features for models from less prestigious marques.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Examples include the Lamborghini Gallardo/Audi R8 and the Audi A4/Volkswagen Passat.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Along with rebadging and badge engineering, platform sharing is common throughout the automotive industry.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Alongside a shared chassis (though unibody construction is nearly universal in cars and many light trucks), platform sharing also standardizes components such as drivetrain, suspensions, components, and other technologies.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] General Motors used the B platform for many of its non-Cadillac full-size vehicles (nearly exclusively from 1959 through 1985), while Chrysler used its B platform for intermediates and its C platform for (non-Imperial) full-size cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Volkswagen Group uses platform sharing as its business strategy to improve its profitability and growth.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For example, Audi uses components from their more pedestrian counterparts, sold as Volkswagen mass-market brands.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] As an effort to place Audi as a "premium" marque, Volkswagen often introduces new technologies in Audi-branded cars before fitting them to mainstream products (such as the Direct-Shift Gearbox).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In production, platform sharing is used extensively, with the modular MQB platform underpinning a range of vehicles from the Audi A1 to the Volkswagen Atlas.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The previous D platform of the 2000s was used for the Volkswagen Phaeton and Bentley Continental GT (built in steel) and the Audi A8 (built in aluminum).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In the Japanese automotive industry, platform sharing has expanded model offerings in North America.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] While the initial Lexus LS was developed specifically for the American market, the later Lexus ES has shared a platform (but not a body) with the Toyota Camry (since 2013, the Toyota Avalon, itself also based on the Camry).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Exclusive primarily to North America, Honda uses a common platform to produce the American version of the Odyssey minivan, also underpinning the Honda Pilot and Honda Passport SUVs, the Acura MDX CUV, and the Honda Ridgeline mid-size pickup truck.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] , originally used by the VE series Holden Commodore.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Although rebadging is intended to save development costs by spreading design and research expenses across several vehicles, it can become problematic if not implemented properly.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Utilizing multiple car brands under a single parent manufacturer can significantly increase selling costs, as each model line must be marketed separately, necessitating a distinct dealership network.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Inappropriate use of rebadging can also negatively impact overall sales by causing "cannibalism" between two or more brands owned by the same company.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] This can occur when there is a failure to develop a distinct image for each brand or when the failure of one version of a model adversely affects its rebadged counterparts.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Through the 2000s, the American Big Three automakers reduced their brand footprint by closing or selling underperforming brands.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] After 2001, Chrysler discontinued its Plymouth brand (following the closure of Eagle in 1998).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In response to the late 2000s recession, Ford ended its ownership of Jaguar, Land Rover, Aston Martin, and Volvo Cars; in 2010, Mercury was closed by Ford.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] General Motors underwent several brand revisions; following the discontinuation of the Geo sub-brand of Chevrolet in 1997, Oldsmobile was closed after 2004 (the oldest American nameplate at the time).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Following its 2009 bankruptcy, GM closed Pontiac, Saturn, and Hummer in 2010; Saab was sold (eventually leading to its demise).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] GM sold its European Opel and Vauxhall brands in 2017 to PSA (now Stellantis).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In response to the 1973 oil crisis, General Motors expanded fuel-efficient offerings beyond its Chevrolet division, reintroducing compact cars to its Buick, Oldsmobile, and Pontiac brands.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Derived from the X-platform Chevrolet Nova, the Pontiac Ventura was introduced for the 1971 model year, with the Buick Apollo and Oldsmobile Omega introduced for 1973.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] These four X-platform vehicles (also known as N-O-V-A from the first letters of their model names) were produced with identical bodies with divisional differences marked only with specific grille, lamp, and body trim variations.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] To expand its footprint in the subcompact segment, the H-body Chevrolet Vega platform was used for the 1975 model year for newly styled variants sold as the Chevrolet Monza, Buick Skyhawk, and Oldsmobile Starfire followed by the 1976 Pontiac Sunbird.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Similarly, to the X-body vehicles, the H-body subcompacts shared common bodies across all four divisions with differing grille, lamp, and body trim variations.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Prior to 1981, the majority of General Motors vehicles were produced with engines designed by their respective divisions.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] From 1981 onward, GM ended its policy of divisionally developed engines, instead offering engines under a singular GM brand.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] As an exception, Cadillac offers division-exclusive engines (the Northstar and Blackwing V8 engine families).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In 1981, GM lost a 1977 lawsuit related to consumers (who purchased 1977 Oldsmobile Delta 88s equipped with a 350 cu in (5.7 L) Chevrolet small-block engine instead of the 350 cu in (5.7 L) Oldsmobile V8 engine).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] At the time of production, GM had downsized its full-size model lines in preparation for another oil crisis and had increased production of V6 engines as the intended standard engine, underestimating consumer demand for Oldsmobile V8 engines.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] To accommodate the increased market demand, nearly 60% of Delta 88s were equipped with a Chevrolet 5.7 L V8 for 1977.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The lawsuit was filed by the state of Illinois, claiming GM falsely advertised the vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In 1981, GM settled the lawsuit with the vehicle buyers and discontinued their company-unique policy of division-specific engines.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Prior to the mid-1970s, the American luxury brands Lincoln and Cadillac offered model lines consisting entirely of full-size two-door and four-door sedans and full-size personal luxury cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] At the beginning of the decade, European automakers began to market their largest sedans as luxury vehicles in North America.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In response to both the 1973 oil crisis and to regain lost market share, both Cadillac and Lincoln introduced smaller vehicles for their brand.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In one of the most controversial uses of rebranding in automotive history, both vehicles were derived from smaller GM and Ford divisional model ranges.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For the 1977 model year, Lincoln released the Lincoln Versailles to match the debut of the Cadillac Seville.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In contrast with the Seville (sharing its chassis underpinnings both the Chevrolet Nova and the Chevrolet Camaro), the Versailles shared nearly its entire body with the Mercury Monarch (itself a counterpart of the Ford Granada); the model line also replaced the previous Mercury Grand Monarch Ghia.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Outsold by the Seville nearly three-to-one, the Versailles sold far under sales predictions and was discontinued early in the 1980 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For 1982, Cadillac released the Cadillac Cimarron to compete against compact European-brand executive sedans.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The smallest Cadillac produced since the 1900s, the Cimarron used the chassis of the GM J-body four-door sedan.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Developed and brought to market less than a year before the J-body was released, Cadillac was left with almost no time to distinguish the Cimarron from its divisional counterparts from Chevrolet, Buick, Oldsmobile, and Pontiac.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Though sharing nearly its entire exterior with the four-door Chevrolet Cavalier, the Cimarron was priced nearly twice as high as its counterpart.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Additionally, J-body vehicles from other divisions could be equipped nearly identically to the Cimarron for a lower cost.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Though the model line closely matched its Buick Skyhawk and Oldsmobile Firenza counterparts in sales, the Cimarron was discontinued following the 1988 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Though the Lincoln Versailles was largely forgotten after its 1980 discontinuation (its role superseded by the downsizing of the Lincoln Continental for 1982), the Cimarron would cause extensive damage to the Cadillac brand, as its market share declined by almost 50% from 1980 to 1998.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] As of current production, neither Lincoln nor Cadillac has marketed a compact-segment car.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] From 1982 until 1986, the front-wheel drive A platform underpinned the Chevrolet Celebrity, Cutlass Ciera, Pontiac 6000, and Buick Century.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In 1987, Chrysler Corporation acquired American Motors Corporation (AMC) from Renault, leading to the exit of the latter company from the North American market.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] As part of the sale, Chrysler obtained the AMC dealership network, the AMC Eagle line of all-wheel drive cars, and the Jeep line of sport-utility vehicles and pickup trucks.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For 1989, Chrysler established the Jeep-Eagle Division in a strategy to both focus on Jeep and offer specialty cars differentiated from the established Chrysler lines.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Following the retirement of the AMC Eagle Wagon in early 1988 (derived from the 1971 AMC Hornet), Eagle established its product line with the introduction of the 1988 Premier and Medallion (developed by Renault prior to the sale of AMC).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] To expand the product range beyond the two sedans, Chrysler sourced vehicles from Mitsubishi, introducing the 1989 Summit (Dodge/Plymouth Colt) and 1990 Talon (Mitsubishi Eclipse).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] In contrast to the Jeep range, Eagle was marketed towards consumers interested in imported vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For 1992, the Eagle Vision full-size sedan replaced the Premier, becoming the first Eagle-brand vehicle developed by Chrysler.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Positioned between the Dodge Intrepid and Chrysler Concorde, the Eagle Vision shared most exterior trim with the Concorde.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] It was the only Chrysler LH car offered exclusively with a five-passenger interior.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Coinciding with the 1998 Daimler-Chrysler merger, the Eagle brand was discontinued; the singular Jeep brand was integrated as part of Chrysler or Dodge dealership networks.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Chrysler 300M was originally developed as a second generation of the Eagle Vision; following the discontinuation of Eagle, the vehicle continued into production as a Chrysler model, adopting a slightly restyled grille, Chrysler badging, and a Chrysler interior.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For the 1989 model year, Toyota and Nissan introduced the Lexus and Infiniti luxury brands in the United States (following the Acura luxury brand of Honda) with the all-new Lexus LS400 and Infiniti Q45 full-size sedans.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Both brands expanded their model line for 1990, sourcing an existing model line from the Japanese market to rebrand as an entry-level offering.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Lexus ES250 is a four-door sedan derived from the V20 Toyota Camry.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Though visibly similar to the Camry introduced for 1987, the ES250 was a rebranded Toyota Camry Prominent/Vista; a model developed for Japan, the Prominent/Vista (dependent on sales network) is a four-door pillared hardtop sedan with a slightly lower roofline and restyled body panels.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Along with the change to left-hand drive, the ES250 adopted an interior similar to the larger LS (along with similarly styled wheels and taillamps).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Infiniti M30 is a two-door notchback coupe derived from the Nissan Leopard (a model never sold in North America).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Along with the coupe, Infiniti sold the M30 as a two-door convertible (converted in the United States).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] With the exception of its badging and its dashboard (sourced from the left-hand drive Nissan Skyline), the M30 differed from the Leopard primarily in its steering wheel location.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Intended largely as placeholder models, the ES250 and M30 were largely overshadowed by their companion flagship sedans.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Following the end of the 1992 model year, both models were withdrawn (as their Japanese counterparts had ended their model cycles).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] For 1993, the ES250 was replaced by the ES300; while again sharing its body with a Japanese-market Toyota (Toyota Vista/Windom) and its chassis and engine with the Camry, the ES300 shared no resemblance to the American-market Camry.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Infiniti moved away from a two-door coupe entirely, replacing the M30 with the four-door J30 (Nissan Leopard J Ferie in Japan).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Rover CityRover, launched in 2003 as the last vehicle from the MG Rover Group, was a rebadged Tata Indica made in India.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] A variant of rebadging is licensing models to be produced by other companies, typically in another country.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The earliest such vehicle was the Austin 7 (1922–1939), designed and built by Austin Motor Company and licensed to other manufacturers across continents, which became their first-ever model.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Bantam in the US that would eventually build the first Jeep, BMW in Germany, and Nissan in Japan.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Among the post-war cars, the Fiat 124 designed and built by Fiat, Italy was licensed to various other manufacturers from different countries.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] It became a dominant car in many Eastern Europe and West Asian countries.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] The Morris Oxford Series IV built by Morris of England in 1955 would become Hindustan Ambassador in India and was manufactured until 2014.
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] Another example of this is the British Hillman Hunter, which was license-built in Iran as the Paykan, as well as Naza, building vehicles under license from Kia and Peugeot (Naza 206 Bestari).
[src:dodge-mirada/badge-engineering] A similar example of licensed badge-engineered products would be the Volga Siber, a rebadged version of the Chrysler Sebring sedan and the Dodge Stratus sedan produced in Russia from 2008 until 2010.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington has the second-most starts without a win, and finished in the top-ten of NASCAR points twice; in 1978 (ninth) and 1982 (seventh).
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington was loyal to his Mopar cars and engines, as he ran Chryslers and Dodges until 1985 (Chrysler stopped production of raceable body styles in 1983 and they became ineligible two years later) when the company stopped supporting them.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] His best career race and finish was at Talladega in 1979, where he had a powerful enough car to lead a few laps towards the end, and finished third.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington finished one lap ahead of Richard Petty, driving one of Petty's cast-off Dodge Magnums that were left when Petty abandoned Mopar and began driving General Motors vehicles a year earlier, and several other top NASCAR drivers.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington almost always ran his own car, and his operation was a very money-conscious effort.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] His pit crew were almost always unpaid volunteers, and he relied heavily (and almost exclusively) on used equipment with Petty's old Magnums being his primary cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Since Arrington could not afford new cars, his team would have to reconfigure the Petty cars and re-skin them into Dodge Miradas or Chrysler Imperials for a 1981 rule change.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington's two Chrysler Imperials were the last Chrysler products to run in the NASCAR Winston Cup series.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] He ran the car at first in two races in the 1981 season, and in more races (alternating with Dodge Miradas) until April 1985, when at that point the parts supply, even used, for Chrysler products (Chrysler factory support ended in late 1978) dried up.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] He sold one of the Imperials (purchased from Cecil Gordon in 1984) to Phil Goode in April 1985 (Goode raced it till the end of the 1985 season), and his other Imperial was given to the NASCAR Hall of Fame at Talladega, Alabama.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington was always a much-liked man on the NASCAR circuit, and other teams and a small, but loyal fan club pitched in to help keep him racing.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] In 1985 the generosity of rising NASCAR star driver Bill Elliott (who sold Arrington his slightly used Ford Thunderbird race cars and parts on the cheap) kept Arrington driving until 1988.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington's son Joey (who at the age of seventeen served on Buddy's pit crew, and built up his engines), now runs Arrington Manufacturing in Martinsville, Virginia.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] The company builds racing engines (mostly Dodges) for the Craftsman Truck Series, and test engines for Nextel Cup Nationwide series cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington was a regular visitor to his son's company, and often offered advice to young (mostly Dodge) drivers trying to make it in NASCAR racing.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington is a noted figure in NASCAR and Mopar history.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] He began professional NASCAR racing in December 1963 behind the wheel of his Dodge hardtop, and for the next twenty-five years, he never missed a season; finally retiring from the sport in 1988.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] What made Arrington unique in the history of the sport was his absolute dedication and loyalty to Chrysler, and his positive attitude in spite of what often seemed like insurmountable odds.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Being the team owner and driver, Arrington drove Dodges from 1964 all the way through mid-season 1985.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] In 1984 and 1985, his Chrysler Imperial became the last Chrysler product in NASCAR until Dodge reentered the sport in 2001.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] As prolific a racer as Arrington was, and as popular as he still remains among fans, he never won a single NASCAR race.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] In his 560 career starts, he mustered fifteen top-five finishes, and his highest points finish was seventh, achieved in 1982.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Still, Arrington never abandoned the Mopar banner until Mopar completely abandoned him and pulled all parts sponsorships in 1985.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] Arrington died on August 2, 2022, at the age of 84.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] (key) (**Bold** – Pole position awarded by qualifying time.
[src:dodge-mirada/buddy-arrington] *Italics* – Pole position earned by points standings or practice time.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The **Buick Regal** is a line of mid-size cars marketed by Buick since 1973.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal also serves as the basis of the high-performance Grand National, Gran Sport (GS), and Buick GNX coupes.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The turbocharged LD5 3.8L V6 used in the second generation was used to showcase the motorsports presence of the brand; though offered with other vehicles (including Chevrolets and Pontiacs), the turbocharged engine is most commonly associated with the Regal.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] During the 1990s, the V6 regained forced induction, with a supercharger replacing the turbocharger.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In 1999, General Motors commenced sales of its vehicles in China, with the Buick Regal serving as its introductory model of the joint venture SAIC-GM.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] After 2004, Buick retired the model line in North America, as it replaced both the Regal and the Century with the Buick LaCrosse.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Following the introduction of the second-generation Regal for China for 2008, the model line returned to North America for the 2011 model year as a rebadged Opel Insignia, slotted slightly below the LaCrosse.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Following the introduction of the sixth-generation Regal (sourced entirely from Germany) for 2018, GM sold Opel to PSA (now Stellantis), ending sales in North America after the 2020 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Currently, the Insignia B-derived Regal remains in production by SAIC-GM.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In the full-size personal luxury car segment, Buick was the first GM division to market a vehicle (the 1963 Buick Riviera, debuting the GM E-body).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As the segment expanded towards intermediate-size coupes, GM saw the introduction of a repackaged Pontiac Grand Prix for 1969 and an all-new Chevrolet Monte Carlo for 1970.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The same year, Oldsmobile added a notchback roofline to its Cutlass Supreme coupe; repackaging it as an equivalent of the Grand Prix proved successful, as it became the brand's best-selling intermediate.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1973, GM introduced the "Colonnade" generation of its A-body intermediates.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Developed in anticipation of increased rollover safety standards, GM eliminated hardtop rooflines completely (in favor of visually reinforced roof pillars); the designs were marketed as "pillared hardtops" (retaining frameless door glass on all body styles).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick dropped the Skylark nameplate from its A-body range, replacing it with Century (last used in 1958 on its flagship B-body).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As with other Colonnade intermediates, the Century was offered as a two-door and four-door sedan and a five-door station wagon.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] After lagging behind Chevrolet, Oldsmobile, and Pontiac, Buick introduced an intermediate-size personal coupe for 1973, marketing the "Century Regal Colonnade Hardtop coupe".
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Along with a notchback roofline (with side opera windows), the Regal featured its own grille and taillamp lenses.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1973, Buick introduced the Century Regal as the flagship model of its A-body intermediate line.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As with the lower-priced Century Luxus coupe, the Regal shared its notchback roofline with the Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme, and Pontiac Grand Prix.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1974, the Century Regal adopted a four-door sedan from its parent line, which featured a slightly fastback roofline (the Colonnade station wagon only carried the Century Estate nameplate).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1976, the Buick Regal became a distinct model line slotted above the Century.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Interiors were upgraded over standard Century trims, with Regals featuring woodgrain trim on the dashboard and door panels (equipped with door-pull straps).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Bench seats with folding center armrests were standard, upholstered in either cloth, velour, or vinyl upholstery; a 60/40 split-bench seat was optional.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 1976-1977 Regal S/R coupe was offered with reclining bucket seats with corduroy upholstery.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Colonnade-generation Regal saw relatively few changes through its production.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Following revisions related to the 1974 addition of 5-mph bumpers, the front fascia underwent an update for 1976, incorporating rectangular-lens quad headlamps (horizontally-mounted on coupes, vertically stacked on sedans).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Over 500,000 Regal coupes were sold during this generation, though the model lagged behind the Monte Carlo and Cutlass Supreme; the latter had become among the best-selling car lines in America by 1976.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal was most commonly powered by a Buick 350 cu in (5.7 L) V8, which was the standard engine for 1973 and 1974; a Buick 455 cu in (7.5 L) V8 was optional.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1975, Buick intermediates dropped the 455 V8, with the 350 V8 becoming an optional engine for Regal coupes.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1975, a 231 cu in (3.8 L) V6 became the standard engine.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Designed by Buick, the V6 was developed for its initial Special/Skylark compacts in the early 1960s.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In 1967, the tooling for the engine was sold to Kaiser Motors for use in Jeep vehicles (purchased by American Motors in 1970).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In 1974, GM acquired the tooling and the rights to the V6 engine from AMC and reintroduced the Buick V6 engine for 1975.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1975 and 1976, the Century and Regal were the only mid-size cars sold in America to offer V6 engines.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A downsized Regal appeared for the 1978 model year with Buick's new 196 cu in (3.2 L) V6 engine as standard equipment and a revised version of the venerable 231 cu in (3.8 L) V6 as an option (which became standard for 1980).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Initially, a three-speed manual transmission was standard and a four-speed available, but the automatic option filled their places from 1980 onward.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] At the time of introduction, Regals were available exclusively as coupés with the Century nameplate applied to standard equipment sedans and station wagons.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In January 1982 the Century was replaced by an all-new car on the front-wheel drive A platform, which meant that the Regal gained a four-door sedan and five-door station wagon - essentially facelifted and rebadged versions of the previous year's rear-wheel drive Century.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] It was the first time the name appeared on a full model lineup.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The wagon was discontinued after 1983, and the sedan dropped from the lineup the next year.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The base model was equipped with softer-riding luxury suspension.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 1978 Regal could be equipped with a 3,791 cc (3.8 L; 231.3 cu in) Turbocharged V6 engine with automatic transmission; it was known in this configuration as a Regal Sport Coupe.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Buick LeSabre was also available with the turbocharged engine, the only other turbocharged cars available in the U.S. market in 1978 being imports from Mercedes-Benz, Porsche and Saab.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal Sport Coupe also included a firm handling suspension with larger tires and sport wheels.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Bucket seats and a center console with a T-shifter were available.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1980, the Regal was offered in a special **Somerset Limited Edition** trim which featured unique tan and dark blue designer exterior paint, wire wheel covers, sport mirrors, and chrome Somerset badging.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The interior had tan and blue plush velour upholstery, brushed chrome trim, and additional Somerset badging.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A Somerset Limited Edition model was also offered on the restyled 1981 Regal.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] It had unique dark sandstone and camel exterior paint, sport mirrors, and turbine wheels.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The interior's plush velour upholstery was camel with dark brown piping.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A major facelift for 1981 gave the Regal a much more aerodynamic profile, helping make it possible for the car to compete on the NASCAR racing circuit.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The sloping hood and nose of the car made it the favorite of several NASCAR teams, and reduced the drag coefficient by eighteen percent.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Richard Petty drove one to victory in the 1981 Daytona 500, and the car won a majority of the 1981 and 1982 seasons races and won the NASCAR manufacturers title in 1981 and 1982.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick would remain the last marque other than Chevrolet or Ford to win the Cup Series manufacturers championship until Toyota scored its first in 2016.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] It also propelled Buick to #3 in sales after 26 years, remaining in that place through 1983.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] V8s for street use were still available, but had shrunk to 265 cu in (4.3 L) (1980 and 1981 only, Pontiac built), and the V6 was rapidly gaining popularity.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] From 1986 to 1987, the 307 cu in (5.0 L) V8 was available as an option.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 200-4R overdrive transmission was an option with either engine.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In 1978, the first turbocharged Regal was introduced as the Regal Sport Coupe.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Turbo versions were originally offered with either a two- or a four-barrel carburetor and 150 or 165 hp (112 or 123 kW), but the two-barrel option was removed for 1979.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Meanwhile, the four-barrel's maximum output increased to 170 hp (127 kW).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Power remained unchanged until 1982, when it increased to 175 hp (130 kW) and then 180 hp (134 kW) in 1983, when the Regal T-Type replaced the Sport Coupe.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In February 1982, the Grand National debuted, which was named for the NASCAR Winston Cup Grand National Series (the "Grand National" term was part of the Cup series nomenclature until 1986).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick had won the Manufacturers Cup in 1981 and 1982, and wanted to capitalize on its success: "What wins on Sunday, sells on Monday", and hoping to revive their performance image from the 1960s with the Buick Skylark Gran Sport.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] All examples started out as charcoal gray Regals that were shipped off to a subcontractor for finishing.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Originally intended for a run of 100 units, Cars and Concepts of Brighton, Michigan, retrofitted 215 Regals with the GN package.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Most obvious was the light silver-gray Firemist paint added to each side.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Red pinstripes and billboard shadow lettering proclaiming "Buick" were applied.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The wheel opening moldings and rocker panel moldings were blacked out using black vinyl tape.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Finally, a front air dam and rear spoiler were installed.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] On the inside, special "Lear-Siegler" seats were installed.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] These seats are fully adjustable and were covered with silver brandon cloth with black vinyl inserts.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The front seat had Buick's "6" emblem embroidered onto it.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 1982 GN came with a naturally aspirated 252 cu in (4.1 L) V6 engine with 125 hp (93 kW) at 4000 rpm and 205 lb⋅ft (278 N⋅m) of torque at 2000 rpm.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Of the 215 Grand Nationals produced in 1982, at least 35 were based on the Buick Regal Sport Coupe package with the turbocharged 3,791 cc (3.8 L; 231.3 cu in) V6 engine with 175 hp (130 kW) at 4000 rpm and 275 lb⋅ft (373 N⋅m) of torque at 2600 rpm.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Only 2022 Sport coupes were produced in 1982, and the number of cars with both the GN and Sport coupe packages is estimated to be fewer than 50.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Sport Coupe model was renamed the T-Type; 3,732 were produced (180 hp (134 kW) at 4000 rpm and 280 lb⋅ft (380 N⋅m) of torque at 2400 rpm).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The power gains came courtesy of a low-restriction dual exhaust, stainless steel headers (rather than the original cast iron items), and other detail improvements.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Drivability improved thanks to better electronics for the exhaust gas recirculation system and the knock sensor.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The T-Type trim name had been used on other Buicks, starting with the Riviera in 1981 (in 1979 and 1980, it was the S-Type).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Other improvements on the 1983 Regal T-Type included Hydro-Boost II brakes, 200-4R four-speed overdrive transmission replacing the earlier three-speed, and a 3.42 rear axle (7.5").
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Inside there were new bucket seats and a sport steering wheel and quicker steering ratio, while the suspension was honed with a larger diameter anti-roll bar, altered spring rates, and re-valved shock absorbers.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In 1984, the Grand National returned, now in all-black paint.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The turbocharged 3,791 cc (3.8 L; 231.3 cu in) became standard and was refined with sequential fuel injection, distributor-less computer-controlled ignition, and boasted 200 hp (149 kW) at 4400 rpm and 300 lb⋅ft (407 N⋅m) of torque at 2400 rpm.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Only 5,204 turbo Regals were produced that year, only 2,000 of which were Grand Nationals.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Because this was the first year of production of the computer-controlled sequential fuel injection and distributor-less ignition, this is often considered the year and model that started the development of the legendary intercooled Grand Nationals.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The performance of this package was well ahead of its time, and the "little V6" easily kept up with the bigger V8s.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] 1⁄4 mile (402 m) performance was listed at 15.9 seconds at stock boost levels of 10 psi (0.69 bar), while for the same year, the Chevrolet Camaro V6 was listed at 17.0 and the Chevrolet Corvette at 15.2 seconds.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1985, the Grand National remained unchanged.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1986, a modified engine design with air-air intercooling boosted the performance even further to a specified 235 hp (175 kW) at 4000 rpm and 330 lb⋅ft (447 N⋅m) of torque at 2400 rpm.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Grand Nationals (quantity 5,512) and T-Types (quantity 2,384) were both produced in 1986.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1987, performance increased 10 hp, to 245 hp (183 kW) and 355 lb⋅ft (481 N⋅m) of torque; however, no design revisions were made to the engine or systems.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick dropped the T-Type package for Regal for 1987 models and opted for a "T" sport package instead.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Only 7,896 turbo Regals were produced in 1986.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In 1987, when turbo Regals reached their peak in popularity, a total of 27,590 turbo Regals were produced through December, with those models produced between September and December of that year window stickered as "1987½ Buick Grand National" vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1987, a lightweight WE4 option was offered.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Only 1,547 of this variant were produced.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The differences between a WE4 and the Grand National were the interior trim package, wheels, exterior badging, aluminum bumper supports, and aluminum rear drum brakes, unlike the Grand National's cast iron, making the WE4 a lighter and faster car.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The rear spoiler was only available as a dealer-installed option.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] 1987 was the only year the LC2 turbo option was available on any Regal, making a Limited with a vinyl landau roof and a power bulge turbo hood combination possible.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Turbo Regal Limiteds were the second-rarest model of turbo Regals produced, after the GNX, at 1,035.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Turbo Regal Limiteds could be ordered with many options, with most having chrome external trim, but for $35 could have been built with the full blackout trim WO2 option, making them extremely rare.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Similarly, a base Regal could be ordered with the Turbo 6, and the WO2 blackout trim was also available.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Limiteds were treated to a very luxurious interior with plush carpeting, optional bench pillow seats, and a column shift.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] It was also possible to order the 1987 Regal T with the 5.0/307 V8 instead of the turbo 3.8/231 V6.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 1987 model would be the end of the manufacture of the RWD "G-Body" Regal, but GM had to extend the build of the Grand National to meet customer demand into December.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For the final year, 1987, Buick introduced the limited production GNX, for "Grand National Experimental", at $29,900 ($85,399 adjusted for inflation in 2025).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Made in partnership with McLaren Performance Technologies/ASC, Buick produced only 547 GNs with the interior trim package, that were then sent off to McLaren and upgraded into the Buick GNX.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick underrated the GNX at 276 hp (280 PS; 206 kW) at 4400 rpm and a very substantial 360 lb⋅ft (488 N⋅m) at 3000 rpm of torque, although actual output is 300 bhp (304 PS; 224 kW) and 420 lb⋅ft (569 N⋅m).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] This was created to be the "Grand National to end all Grand Nationals".
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Changes made included a special Garrett AiResearch T-3 turbocharger with a ceramic-impeller blowing through a more efficient and significantly larger capacity intercooler with a "Cermatel (ceramic-aluminum) coated" pipe connecting the intercooler to the engine.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A GNX-specific EPROM, low-restriction exhaust with dual mufflers, reprogrammed turbo Hydramatic 200-4R transmission with a custom torque converter and transmission cooler, a unique differential cover, and panhard rod included more of the performance modifications.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Exterior styling changes include vents located on each front fender, 16 inch black mesh style wheels with VR-speed rated tires, and deletion of the hood and fender emblems.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The interior changes of the GNX included a serial number on the dash plaque and a revised instrument cluster providing Stewart-Warner analog gauges, including an analog turbo boost gauge.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The GNX used a unique torque arm that was mounted to a special, GNX only, rear differential cover, for increased traction.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The torque arm rear suspension alters the suspension geometry, making the body lift while planting the rear tires down, resulting in increased traction.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] GNX #001 is the 1986 prototype currently owned by Buick and sometimes makes appearances at car shows around the US.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The "Dark Side" contrasted with the more common V8 Mustangs and Camaros that were popular at the time.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A new Regal appeared in October 1987 on the GM W platform as the first vehicle on that platform; this generation ran with few changes for nine years.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Though the new Regal returned to Buick's original concept in being offered only as a coupe and in being aimed once again squarely at the personal luxury buyer, it departed from tradition in being the first front-wheel-drive model, and in having no serious performance option or edition.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Neither a V8 engine nor a turbocharged V6 was offered; the only engine available for 1988 was the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6, producing 125 hp (93 kW).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] From mid-1990, owing to the declining personal luxury car market, a four-door sedan version of the Regal was re-introduced (simultaneously as the Cutlass Supreme and Grand Prix, the latter offered as a sedan for the first time).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] However, sales of the new sedan were delayed until the 1991 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The four-door version was intended as a replacement for the A-body based Century, however, the popularity of that model meant that it would remain in production as a lower priced alternative to the Regal until both cars were redesigned for 1997.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] This generation saw the installation of Dynaride, which was an air compressor that would pressurize the rear Chapman Struts to maintain a level overall ride height.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A badge was installed on the dashboard to the left of the steering column on all vehicles equipped.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] It was not available on vehicles equipped with Gran Touring Suspension, which instead used a stiffer setup with traditional hydraulic rear struts.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal was initially offered in base *Custom* and upscale *Limited* trim lines.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1989, the *Gran Sport* trim line was added, featuring aluminum wheels, body side cladding and a console-mounted shifter attached to the 4-speed automatic.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In mid-1990, the Regal gained the option of the Buick 3.8 L V6 with "Tuned-Port-Injection" (TPI).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 3800 V6 was unique to the Regal amongst the W-body cars, differentiating it from the mechanically similar Chevrolet Lumina, Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme, and Pontiac Grand Prix.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Anti-lock brakes were made standard on all but the base *Custom* cars from 1992.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1993, the Regal sedan received a minor facelift with a new hood and larger grille more reminiscent of the larger Buick models, as well as larger taillights.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Along with this change came the introduction of an all new electronically controlled 4T60-E automatic transmission to replace the previous 4T60.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1994, a driver's-side airbag was added, along with standard ABS on all models, standard power windows, and 20 hp (15 kW) more in the base engine due to a revised intake manifold and cylinder head.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The *Limited* coupe was deleted; only the *Custom* and *Gran Sport (GS)* coupes remained.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 1995, another facelift occurred with new smoothed out bumpers, taillights, and body cladding.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The interior was completely redesigned to be more streamlined and ergonomically friendly with dual front airbags now standard.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] All models were now modified to be OBD II compliant.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A special "Olympic Gold" edition (also available on Skylark) was added to celebrate Buick's partnership with the 1996 Summer Olympics, complete with gold accents and traditional Olympic logos on the exterior and interior.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For the 1997 model year, the Century and Regal once again rode upon the same platform; the revised W platform that was shared with the Oldsmobile Intrigue, the Pontiac Grand Prix, the Chevrolet Lumina and Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Differences between the Regal and Century were mostly cosmetic.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As the upmarket version, the Regal offered larger engines and fancier trim, and once again boasted a newer version of the 3.8 L V6.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] While the Century was mainly a reliable, economy-minded car based upon the W-body, the Regal was fitted with many amenities, including heated leather seats (optional on the Century), a Monsoon 8-speaker surround sound system, dual climate control, and expansive interior space.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Few changes occurred during this version's seven-year run.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] It offered 5-passenger seating on all trim levels like the Pontiac Grand Prix and Oldsmobile Intrigue (formerly Cutlass Supreme), unlike their predecessors that had optional 6-passenger seating and the Buick Century (formerly built on the A platform) which had standard 6-passenger seating.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] This period held the fastest Buick since the days of the 1987 GNX: the Buick Regal GS.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] This car was now supercharged instead of turbocharged, and produced 240 hp (179 kW) and 280 lb⋅ft (380 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] When introduced in January 1997, Buick advertised the Regal GS as "The official car of the supercharged family".
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick also released two other model types, the LSE and the GSE.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The LSE stayed with the 200 hp (149 kW) engine with upgrades and the GSE stayed with the 240 hp (179 kW) supercharged engine with upgrades.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Also, in 2000 Buick came out with a concept GSX that had an intercooled 3.8 L, but was supercharged rather than turbocharged.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] From 2001 to 2004 Buick offered a Joseph Abboud appearance package on both the GS and LS models.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] This package included either a solid taupe or two-tone taupe/chestnut leather seats, two-tone leather-wrapped steering wheel, leather shifter handle and boot, 16-inch aluminum wheels; and Joseph Abboud signature emblems on the front doors, floor mats, front-seat headrests, and taillights.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The North American Regal was replaced in 2005 by the Buick LaCrosse, also built on the W platform.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The final 2004 Buick Regal rolled off the assembly line on June 1, 2004.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal LS from the factory had a 1/4 mile (≈400 m) elapsed time (ET) of 15.8 seconds and could do 0-60 mph in under 8 seconds.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The supercharged Regal GS had a 1/4 mile ET of 14.9 seconds, and acceleration to 60 mph (97 km/h) took 6.7 seconds.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal GS, equipped with the supercharged 3.8 liter V6 engine (L67) produced 240 hp (179 kW) & 280 lb⋅ft (380 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal LS was EPA rated at 19/30 MPG city/freeway while the supercharged Regal GS was EPA rated at 18/27 MPG city/freeway.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In the 2003 and 2004 model years, Buick officially offered — in collaboration with Troy, Michigan based tuners, Street Legal Performance, aka SLP Performance — the Buick Regal GSX, with dealer-supplied and installed options for both LS and GS models.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The SLP GSX offered three packages, marketed as *stages*.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Stage 1 package added 10 horsepower with the addition of a dual stainless steel cat-back exhaust system and free-flowing cold air induction system.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Stage 2 package added a Hypertech Power Programmer with an SLP custom calibration — good for an extra 20 horsepower on top of the Stage 1 package.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Stage 3 package added a 3.5-inch smaller diameter supercharger pulley to increase the boost.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] With an advertised 30 more horsepower than stock, the Stage 3 GSX was conservatively rated at 270 hp (201 kW) and 312 lb⋅ft (423 N⋅m) of torque.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As GSX parts remained directly available from SLP for many years, Regal GS sedan owners could have their cars independently customized to GSX appearance and performance by SLP dealers, including for Regal GS models from 1997 to 2004.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] An authentic Buick GSX can be verified from an SLP door jamb label with the correct part number for the kit.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] General Motors and Shanghai Automotive Industry Corporation (SAIC) established a joint venture in 1997 called Shanghai GM, and had begun assembling the Buick Regal in Shanghai, China in April 1999.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal has sold well in the Chinese market as a large, relatively luxurious model, despite its high price, costing more than the North American version.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Chinese market Regal has different front- and rear-end styling compared to the North American version and different engines, including the 2.0 L *L34*, the 2.5 L *LB8* V6 and the 3.0 L *LW9* V6.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Gearbox choices were a 4-speed automatic for V6 models, while four-cylinder variants are paired with an exclusive 5-speed manual gearbox.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] V6 models had a set of black dashboard gauges, while the four-cylinder models had white dashboard gauges.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] These models also had slightly different names: the entry-level model was the *New Century*, with more upscale models carrying the *GL* and *GLX* names.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Production for this generation ended in November 2008 in China being replaced by the Opel Insignia-based Regal.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Chinese-built Regal was also sold in the Philippines from 2005 to 2006 as the Chevrolet Lumina, where it replaced the Opel Vectra.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Chevrolet Lumina was discontinued from the Filipino market in 2006, leaving GM again without a mid-size sedan until the introduction of the eighth generation Chevrolet Malibu in 2013.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The fifth-generation Buick Regal is a four-door, five-passenger, midsized sedan with a front engine, front-wheel drive layout.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] According to GM published information, more than 41 percent of Regal buyers in the US came from non-General Motors brands, and more than 60 percent of CXL Turbo buyers were under the age of 55.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The fifth generation Buick Regal rides on GM's Epsilon II platform and is mostly identical to the Opel Insignia.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] It first went into production in Rüsselsheim, Germany, in 2008.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Shanghai GM twin of the Insignia was introduced in China as Buick Regal in December, 2008 for the 2009 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] GM originally planned to sell a modified version of the Opel Insignia in North America as the second generation Saturn Aura, but changed strategy after deciding to discontinue the Saturn brand.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal utilizes unibody construction with galvanized steel front fenders, hood, roof and door panels and thermoplastic polyolefin (TPO) bumper covers.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The North American Regal weighs about 13 lb (6 kg) more than an equivalent Opel Insignia due to increased structural support in the B-pillar necessary to meet U.S. rollover standards.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick's product manager director Roger McCormack stated in a 2010 consumer webchat that a coupé version was under heavy consideration, as well as the possibility for further body styles such as a convertible.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A Buick-badged Insignia Sports Tourer was also spied, but the following year a Buick spokesperson declared that there were no plans to sell a Regal wagon.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] GM presented the fifth-generation Regal to North American dealers on October 14, 2009, and introduced the Regal to the public in November 2009 at the LA Auto Show.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Sales of the Regal began in February 2010.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In North America, the Regal is positioned below the larger, more expensive LaCrosse and above the Verano compact sedan which debuted late in the 2011 calendar year.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Production of the Shanghai GM variant of the Regal began in November 2008 and ended in July 2017.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] North American production at General Motors of Canada's Oshawa, Ontario, assembly plant was confirmed on November 25, 2009, and production began at Oshawa Car Assembly in February 2011.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The initial production for the North American market was done together with its Opel twin the Opel Insignia in the Adam Opel AG's Rüsselsheim, Germany assembly plant from March 1, 2010, to March 25, 2011 (33,669 cars in 2010 and 12,637 in 2011).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal debuted in North America with a 2.4L DOHC I4 engine rated at 182 hp (136 kW) and 172 lb⋅ft (233 N⋅m) of torque, using a Hydra-Matic 6T45 six-speed automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 2011 Regal manufactured in North America was offered in a single trim level, marketed as CXL, offered with two engine choices and seven option packages.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick had planned to offer a lower-level trim called CX with cloth seats and a higher level trim called CXS, but those trim levels were not offered.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The 2.0L turbo is the first direct-injected turbocharged production car capable of running on any blend of gasoline or E85 ethanol.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] At the 2010 North American International Auto Show in Detroit, GM showed a concept GS version of the Regal based on the Opel Insignia OPC and the Vauxhall Insignia VXR.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The concept featured a 2.0L, 270 hp (201 kW), 295 lb⋅ft (400 N⋅m) high-output DOHC I4 turbocharged Ecotec engine, a 6-speed manual transmission and all-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The production GS left most of the concept specifications intact, but is front-wheel drive.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The GS features Buick's Interactive Drive Control System with GS mode, a choice of an FGP Germany F40-6 six-speed manual or Aisin AF-40 (G2) six-speed automatic transmission, high performance brakes with Brembo front calipers and high performance strut (HiPerStrut) front suspension.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] 19 inch wheels were offered standard, with 20 inch forged aluminum wheels available as an option.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The production version is equipped with GS-only high-output version of the Ecotec 2.0L turbo engine with 270 hp (201 kW) at 5300 rpm and 295 lb⋅ft (400 N⋅m) of torque at 2400 rpm.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The GM LHU engine used in the GS trim makes 135 hp per liter - Buick's highest specific output ever.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The GS has a quoted 0 to 60 mph (97 km/h) time of 6.7 seconds (Motor Trend achieved 6.3 seconds) and a quarter mile time of 14.9 seconds.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The GS went on sale in fall 2011 as a 2012 model.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Shanghai GM's locally produced variant of the Regal GS went on sale in China on September 15, 2011.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The output of the 2.0L Turbo SIDI engine is 162 kW (217 hp), which is about 40 kW (54 hp) less than the production US-model.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The torque is 350 N⋅m (258 lb⋅ft). and the top speed is claimed as 232 km/h (144 mph).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The car is only offered in this case as a front-wheel-drive.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] There exist also some interior and exterior differences between the American and Chinese models.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 2016, the Regal added a new Sport Touring Edition which included unique 18-inch aluminum black pocket wheels and a rear lip spoiler.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] This remained in the lineup for this generation's final model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Beginning in 2011, Buick began offering the eAssist system in the Regal, The 2012 model year Regal is the second GM vehicle to offer eAssist after the 2012 Buick LaCrosse.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The eAssist system is standard in the LaCrosse 2.5 L I4, but the eAssist powertrain is optional in the Regal.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The eAssist system adds a lithium-ion battery housed in the trunk, along with regenerative braking, engine stop/start, fuel cut-off, grille louvres that close at speed, underbody panels and low-rolling resistance tires.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The eAssist system adds up to 15 hp (11 kW) to the standard 2.4L Ecotec engine during acceleration.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Fuel economy for the Regal with eAssist is estimated at 26 mpg‑US (9.0 L/100 km; 31 mpg‑imp) city, 37 mpg‑US (6.4 L/100 km; 44 mpg‑imp) highway.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] GM presented an updated 2014 Regal at the 2013 New York Auto Show.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Changes included a revised interior and exterior, an increase to 258 hp (192 kW) and 295 lb·ft (400 N·m) of torque for the CXL Turbo and an available all-wheel drive option for the 2.0L engine/6-speed automatic transmission equipped vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Changes for the GS included revised interior and exterior, a drop in power to match that of the CXL Turbo, and available an all-wheel-drive option offered for the 2.0L / six-speed automatic transmission equipped vehicles.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The six-speed manual transmission was offered in the front-wheel-drive variant.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick's VentiPorts reappeared starting with 2014 models, a styling feature first used by Buick in 1949.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For model year 2014, safety features included forward collision warning, lane-departure warning, blind-spot monitoring, rear cross-traffic alert, and a following-distance indicator.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The foregoing are all part of a Driver Confidence package, while collision preparation, which pre-loads the brake system ahead of an imminent collision, and adaptive cruise control are available separately.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] On April 4, 2017, GM presented the sixth-generation 2018 Buick Regal at the GM Design Dome in Warren, Michigan; sales of the model line began in China on July 21, 2017.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As with the Buick Cascada, the Regal became a captive import, as Buick sourced production of the model line entirely from Opel in Rüsselsheim, Germany.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Derived from the Opel/Vauxhall Insignia B, the American-market Regal also gained a third divisional counterpart, as the model became the basis of the Holden ZB Commodore (the final generation of the Commodore line).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal moved to the GM E2XX (third-generation Epsilon) platform, adding 3.6 inches of wheelbase.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] While most closely related to the ninth (final) generation Chevrolet Malibu, it also shared its underpinnings with the third-generation Buick LaCrosse.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Though growing in size, a key objective of the platform update was weight reduction, with 300–500 lb (136–227 kg) of curb weight removed.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In a major design change, the Regal four-door sedan became exclusive to China, with all Regal sedans in North America moving to a five-door liftback configuration.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal TourX station wagon was introduced for 2018, becoming the first Regal station wagon since 1983.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Replacing the previous Regal four-door sedan, the Regal Sportback is a 5-door liftback sedan; the hatchback was incorporated within a fastback roofline, allowing for additional cargo room and flexibility.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Buick offered three standard trims: 1SV (base), Preferred, and Essence, along with the flagship Avenir trim.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Sportback also served as the basis of the high-performance Regal GS (see below).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Fitted with a 250 hp *LTG* 2.0L turbocharged I4 engine, the Sportback was offered with either front-wheel drive (260 lb⋅ft (353 N⋅m) of torque, 9-speed automatic) or optional all-wheel drive (295 lb⋅ft (400 N⋅m) of torque, 8-speed automatic).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Buick Regal TourX is a 5-door station wagon, serving as the divisional counterpart of the Opel/Vauxhall Insignia Country Tourer and the Holden Commodore ZB Calais Tourer.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Developed as a rugged-style station wagon with plastic body cladding, slightly raised ride height, and standard all-wheel drive, the TourX was developed as a competitor of the Subaru Outback and the Volvo Cross Country lines, though marketed towards sportier touring than heavier off-road use.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Insignia Country Tourer was a body style introduced during the previous generation, but was ultimately not produced or imported by GM.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The first Regal station wagon in 35 years, the 2018 TourX was the first Buick station wagon of any kind since the 1996 retirement of the Roadmaster and Century Estates.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Sized between the Subaru Outback and Volvo V90, the TourX was one of the largest station wagons sold in North America; its 73.5 cubic feet of cargo space matched the Outback and was the most of any Buick (with the exception of the three-row Buick Enclave).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Fitted with the 250 hp *LTG* turbocharged I4 (295 lb⋅ft (400 N⋅m) of torque), the TourX only used an 8-speed automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Regal GS (Gran Sport) is the highest-performance version of the Buick Regal.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Returning from the previous generation, the Regal GS is the counterpart of the Opel/Vauxhall Insignia GSi (replacing the previous OPC) and the Holden Commodore VXR.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In keeping with the previous generation, the GS featured a higher-performance powertrain, sportier styling, and upgrading suspension and brakes.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In a major change, the GS now shared the standard all-wheel drive of its Opel counterpart.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The GS shared its liftback body with the Regal Sportback, but the exterior is fitted with its own grille, front and rear bumpers, 19-inch wheels (the previous 20-inch wheels were retired), and an integrated decklid spoiler.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The interior was fitted with heavily-bolstered front seats, a digital instrument cluster, and GS-specific trim.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As the turbocharged LTG from the previous GS became the standard engine for the Sportback and TourX (retuned slightly), the E2XX GS adopted its 310 hp 3.6L V6 engine from the Holden Commodore and Buick LaCrosse, paired with a 9-speed automatic transmission.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The most powerful Regal ever produced, the 2018–2020 GS was the first vehicle in the model line to eclipse the official (rated) power output of the 1987 Buick GNX.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For China, 2018 brought a third-generation Regal, as SAIC-GM began local production of the Opel Insignia B, marketing it between the Verano and LaCrosse sedans.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] While sharing the E2XX platform and a visually similar exterior, the SAIC-produced Regal differed substantially from its Opel-designed counterpart, as it was designed as a four-door sedan with a traditional decklid.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In China, neither the Sportback nor the TourX have been sold; the four-door has never been exported under any nameplate.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] The Chinese-market Regal (sold in front-wheel drive only) was initially sold in four trims: 20T (1.5L turbo I4), 28T (2.0L turbo I4), GS (2.0L turbo I4), and 30H hybrid (1.6L I4 + EV motors).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Turbocharged Regals were fitted with a 9-speed automatic transmissions while the hybrid was fitted with a CVT.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] SAIC-GM Regals were visually similar to Opel-assembled units, with non-GS vehicles closest in design to Essence-trim Sportbacks (though using the digital instrument panel of the GS).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 2021, the Regal underwent a model update, receiving a restyled grille and updated dashboard and center console (with a pushbutton gear selector).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 2022, the trim levels were reduced to Luxury and GS.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] For 2024, a second facelift, concentrating primarily on the front fascia, brought the Regal in line with the Buick "Pure Design" style (seen on Buick American SUVs), giving the model a revised Buick tri-shield emblem.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] As a running change during 2025, SAIC-GM debuted a third facelift for the GS, combining the 2018-2023 grille size with the updated Buick tri-shield.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In response to poor feedback to the "Pure Design" facelift, the company also introduced the updated GS front fascia as a replacement body kit.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In December 2019, General Motors announced that it would stop importing the Buick Regal for North America after the 2020 model year.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Following the 2020 withdrawal of the Cascada and LaCrosse, Buick ended its 113-year run of manufacturing and marketing cars, that is sedans and sedan derivatives, in North America — in favor of sport utility vehicles (SUVs).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] Alongside shifting consumer tastes, the discontinuation of the Regal in North America was also influenced by the sale of Opel and Vauxhall to PSA Group.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] While the latter did not operate in North America in 2017, at the end of 2019, PSA Group acquired FCA, which created Stellantis (the current parent company of Chrysler in North America).
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] In China, SAIC-GM continues to produce the Opel-designed Regal sedan, slotted between the Verano and LaCrosse sedans; the standard Regal and Regal GS underwent a model update for 2021.
[src:dodge-mirada/buick-regal] A total of 114 Regals were sold in Mexico between 2017 and 2019.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:dodge-mirada/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The **Dodge Mirada** is a mid-sized, rear-wheel drive coupe manufactured and marketed by Dodge for the model years 1980 to 1983, sharing the Chrysler J platform along with its badge engineered variants, the second generation Chrysler Cordoba and the Imperial.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Production of the Mirada reached just under 53,000 units, staying relatively unchanged during its four-year run, with the exception of paint colors and engines.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The Mirada was marketed as a sporty personal luxury car with limited advertising and marketing during a period when Chrysler was in deep financial difficulty.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The Mirada was designed after the Cordoba's design was locked in, with various changes made to distinguish it and make it more sporting.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Chief designer Ernie Barry had to include the landau roof even though the design team would have preferred not to, as such "classic" features were favored by Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The front end was from flexible plastic, with a grille design inspired by the "coffin-nosed" Cord 810/812.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The base models all received a basic metal roof with a chrome beauty strip extending from the bottom of the opera windows and across the roof.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] A power sunroof, or a glass T-top roof, were both offered as options for a sportier look; while a vinyl landau roof, or a "cabriolet roof", which was basically a mock convertible top with a blocked out quarter window, were both offered for a more luxurious look.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The T-tops and landau were offered every year except for 1983, and the cabriolet top was offered every year.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] A power sunroof was offered for 1980 and 1981.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Base models came with 15” steel wheels with turbine-like hubcaps, or polished ten-spoke, 15” aluminum wheels with painted sections and bright chrome center caps.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The Mirada came standard with a brushed aluminum finish on the instrumental panel, with faux woodgrain finish offered as an option.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The base seats were cloth Sport bucket seats, while optional seats included vinyl Sport bucket seats, cloth and vinyl 60/40 split bench seats, and leather and vinyl bucket seats.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Since the Mirada could be chosen with either a column shift or floor shift, the bench seat was only offered with the column shifter.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Buyers had the choice of either an AM/FM stereo or an AM/FM/cassette stereo, an AM/FM/8-track stereo, and a Chrysler CB radio could be chosen as well.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Available steering wheels included two iterations of base 2-spoke wheels, an optional 3-spoke Mopar "Tuff Wheel" and an optional 4-spoke sport wheel.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Manual windows were standard on the base model, but the power windows from the CMX could be ordered on the base models as well.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The 3.7 L inline slant-6 engine was available in the base Mirada, with the 5.2 L V8 offered as optional, and the code E58 360 5.9 L V8 available in the Mirada CMX, though only in 1980.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] For unexplained reasons the 360 was not available in any Chrysler automobiles from 1981 and on.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] All of these engines were mated to the A904 automatic transmission except the 360 (5.9L), which received the stronger A727.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] With the 185-horsepower 360, it was one of the fastest American cars available in 1980, on par with the Chevrolet Corvette.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The suspension of the Mirada utilized transverse torsion bars in the front and leaf springs with a sway bar in the rear.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] A "sport handling package" was offered, which included heavy-duty shock absorbers, torsion bar bushings, springs, as well as anti-sway bars in both the front and rear.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] The braking system used power assisted disc brakes in the front and drum brakes in the rear.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] It was hoped that the Mirada would reopen the door to Dodge success in NASCAR racing, as the nameplate had not won a race since November 1977.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Lee Iacocca personally called Richard Petty, a longtime Dodge driver, in late October 1980 and asked him to build and test a race spec Mirada, saying Chrysler would supply Petty Enterprises the necessary body sheetmetal and engine parts Petty would need to build and campaign the car.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Petty, who had left Dodge for General Motors in 1978, agreed, and had his team immediately set about and built a Mirada-based race-car.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] A few other teams including Junior Johnson's team built race-spec Miradas to test.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Johnson's team would have been a major coup for Dodge, as they had been running GM cars since the early 1970s and the team had just signed Darrell Waltrip away from DiGard Motorsports to drive for them (Waltrip having won 22 races in GM cars prior to this).
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] After their car was built, the Petty team thought the Mirada looked like a great race car, and some initial testing pleased the longtime Dodge driver.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] A January 17, 1981, test session at Daytona Speedway where around 15,000 Petty fans showed up to watch.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] However the Mirada was 8 mph (13 km/h) slower than the GM and Ford cars of the day.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] This testing of the car, as well as the Junior Johnson team's testing, revealed that while it looked fairly aerodynamic, the bodystyle actually had a very high coefficient of drag that made it incapable of speeds over 185 mph.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] However, two small and independent racing teams, Arrington Racing (which was using secondhand rebadged Petty Dodges) and Negre Racing, decided to make a go of the car and campaigned it during the 1981 to 1984 racing seasons.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Arrington managed 17 top-ten finishes during those years, though all were on short (1 mile or less) length tracks.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] A few other drivers (Dave Marcis in four races, and Dick May in three) ran Miradas occasionally in 1981, but the cars were either plagued with mechanical issues, or finished several laps off the leaders.
[src:dodge-mirada/dodge-mirada] Up until the end of 1984, Miradas raced from time to time, but without much success, and ultimately led to Dodge disappearing from NASCAR until 2001.
